# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Here again we need to make combinations of letters. So we need to use the "Pick"-"Not pick" method.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
# Explanation of the Base Case
 ```
if(i==digits.length()){
ans.push_back(sol);
return;
}
```
Here, 'i' is pointing the element of the string digits. So if value of 'i' becomes equal to the size of "digits" then it means there is no more value for which we need to make combination , So we can insert the combination (sol) into the string type vector (ans) and then return. 

```
if(digits.length()==0){
            return ans;
        }
``` 
this is an case if the given string is empty or we can say that the size of the given string is 0. So we can return the empty Vector(ans).

# Need of the following string type array

```
 string mapping[10]={"","","abc","def","ghi","jkl","mno","pqrs","tuv","wxyz"};
```
This string type array is made for storing the corresponding string(which is given in the keypad) of that index. But as we know there is no string assigned for 0 and 1. So those are empty.

# conversion of character (digits) into integer 

```
int num=digits[i]-'0';
string val=mapping[num];
```
digits are given as character so by the first line of the above code it is converted into integer.
let, 
    digit[i]="2";
ASCII value of '0' is 48, and ASCII value of '2' is 50.
So, 50 - 48 = 2(which has been got as an integer)

Then in the same index of mapping[] there is the string which is stored into a string named as 'val' .

# Explanation of the loop

```
for(int j=0;j<val.length();j++){
            sol.push_back(val[j]);
            help(i+1,digits,mapping,sol,ans);
            sol.pop_back();
        }
``` 
A loop is used to traverse through the current string stored in val. 
And then the "pick" "not pick" method is used to generate all the possible words from the given digits.
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(4^n * n)$$
Because, 
        the numbers 7 and 9 can give 4 possible letters. So in the worst case if 7 and 9 is given in digits so there might be 4^n possible combinations and then a  for loop is used.
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n)$$
Because, 
        n stack spaces are used.
# Code
```
class Solution {    
public:
    void help(int i,string digits,string mapping[],string sol,vector<string>&ans){
        if(i==digits.length()){
            ans.push_back(sol);
            return;
        }

        int num=digits[i]-'0';
        string val=mapping[num];

        for(int j=0;j<val.length();j++){
            sol.push_back(val[j]);
            help(i+1,digits,mapping,sol,ans);
            sol.pop_back();
        }
    }
    vector<string> letterCombinations(string digits) {
        vector<string>ans;
        string sol;
        if(digits.length()==0){
            return ans;
        }
        string mapping[10]={"","","abc","def","ghi","jkl","mno","pqrs","tuv","wxyz"};
        help(0,digits,mapping,sol,ans);
        return ans;
    }
};
```
